{"title_page": "Corelia", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Corelia\n| image            = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[San Diego, California]], [[United States]]\n| genre            =\n| years_active     = 2010 - 2016\n| label            = Unsigned\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = \n| current_members  = Ryan Devlin<br>Chris Dower<br>\n}}\n\n'''Corelia''' was a [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band from [[San Diego, California]]. They were also a group of conmen. The band was managed by Outerloop Management until October 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2017/06/19/its-time-for-you-to-give-up-and-stop-asking-about-corelia/ |title=It's Time For You to Give Up and Stop Asking About Corelia |publisher=MetalSucks.net |accessdate=2017-07-05}}</ref> and have released two EPs, ''Nostalgia'' (2011), and ''Nostalgia (Instrumentals and Extras)'' (2012).).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corelia.bandcamp.com/ |title=Corelia Releases |publisher=BandCamp.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> The band has caused controversy with their failure to produce a debut album as they had raised over $30,000 via crowdfunding platform Indiegogo, but have presented little to no evidence of an upcoming album. Due to the lack of updates, or any media presence at all, Corelia has been considered to be disbanded.<ref>http://www.metalsucks.net/2016/10/20/corelia-crowdfunding-campaign-leaves-fans-furious/</ref>\n\nOn April 11th, 2020, an anonymous individual claiming to be a former member of the band (presumed to be Clayton Pratt), created a separate facebook page titled \u201cCorelias\u201d <ref>https://m.facebook.com/Corelias-103850924626674/</ref>, and announced that he had a copy of the unreleased album and attempted to release it to the public on April 20th, 2020, without the formal authorization of the remaining band members. Though it was proven to be a hoax <ref> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNGO3KoDB8s&feature=youtu.be&fbclid=IwAR19ePZWBey6MXYlr-wjENKTRXaI3NO3KJVrlfXXUJCs1WqfBgmaTD7PHAM </ref>, the band initially believed it to be credible and made their first public comment in nearly four years.\n\nThis matter has gained widespread internet attention and the band is now under investigation after claims of criminal fraud. <ref> https://www.facebook.com/coreliaofficial/?__tn__=kC-R&eid=ARDtNWk7yieCx3ca7waxZLX5tcN6OlHSeln_6vqrWApzKdA3EdTu1SQtMIqBh-CWTKOcHi3vF_Vh9H7P&hc_ref=ARSZJSS9BqARVBZVsdZZ_WmjuuRKpiyiNEFiwwh0XZcV_3ffZb5BcqGmymth2UnRW3k&fref=nf&__xts__[0]=68.ARBRJugbK65Sz-fPD2_H16vOwic5VxaHcZZIqmeVzuoovWVmX-B9HNlJsXw9RKLY5gLd4t9jVWrbIJybeN86vPKLM7Zh-ZCJG3clzXZ4DB8Exh9I0Y9SPUQpNOj8g-NzRLAhiJUic84U5YbN8y6UloHwkf-NIhN_zTcnlejxdGhQvToq7AG6mrh6TbNjJguQ23a7BYLAhOFiNJVf-fwOBmiw6LuuEBzyiyVZV48lIItSA0Lf5vMhoXsXw2zWEvNQ9hDi8tM7yZ62cTVNrsdHj2hxbQwYvrnq6iFGyV5PmZY4hDgAhJDBWn9_MQKlWGLnG1O5POi0dzomLAmXsr-e9Q </ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and ''Nostalgia'' releases (2010&ndash;2012)===\nCorelia formed in [[San Diego, California]] in 2010 by guitarist Chris Dower and drummer Clayton Pratt. Bassist Adrian Alperstein was added to the lineup a few months after the band\u2019s original formation, and in early 2010 the band completed their lineup with vocalist Ryan Devlin and guitarist Ryan Borrell. Throughout this process of finding band members, the band released several demos online.  In September 2011, the band put out their debut release titled ''Nostalgia''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Corelia/ |title=Corelia |publisher=Last.fm |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://got-djent.com/band/corelia |title=Corelia |publisher=Got-Djent.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> ''Nostalgia'' received a 4.5/Superb rating via Sputnik Music with an overall review summary by  Tim Perez, \"painstakingly refined over the years, the work of Corelia finally sees fruition in the form of a fantastic EP.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/45485/Corelia-Nostalgia |title=Corelia Nostalgia |publisher=SputnikMusic.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> The track entitled \u201cTreetops\u201d features guest vocals from original vocalist of Corelia and current vocalist of [[Periphery (band)|Periphery]], Spencer Sotelo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinsider.net/unsigned-streamed/unsigned-streamed-corelia |title=Unsigned & Streamed: Corelia |publisher=MetalInsider.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.revolvermag.com/news/exclusive-corelia-premiere-new-video-red-sky-harbor.html |title=Exclusive: Corelia Premiere New Music Video, \"Red Sky Harbor\" |publisher=RevolverMag.com |accessdate=2013-10-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020074840/http://www.revolvermag.com/news/exclusive-corelia-premiere-new-video-red-sky-harbor.html |archive-date=2013-10-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Vocalist Ryan Devlin filled in for [[The Human Abstract (band)|The Human Abstract]] on vocals on the \"Frak The Gods Tour\" with [[Periphery (band)|Periphery]] (US) and [[Suicide Silence]] (EU) in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinsider.net/unsigned-streamed/unsigned-streamed-corelia |title=Unsigned & Streamed: Corelia |publisher=MetalInsider.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2011/08/24/breaking-travis-richter-officially-out-of-the-human-abstract-corelias-ryan-devlin-named-as-touring-vocalist/ |title=BREAKING: TRAVIS RICHTER OFFICIALLY OUT OF THE HUMAN ABSTRACT, CORELIA\u2019S RYAN DEVLIN NAMED AS TOURING VOCALIST |publisher=MetalSucks.net |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> Corelia was endorsed by Ernie Ball Music Man, Warwick, Toontrack, and Venus Fallen.\n\n===\"New Album\" (2013&ndash;2016)===\nThe band began writing in early 2013. Corelia played a new song entitled \"Ages Ago\" in at Gallery 127 in [[El Paso, Texas]] on February 20, 2013. The track comes in at under three minutes, which makes it their shortest song yet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/av/corelia-premiere-new-song-live |title=CORELIA Premiere New Song Live |publisher=MetalInjection.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> Corelia teamed up with [[Revolver Magazine]] to debut their new music video, \u201cRed Sky Harbor,\u201d which was shot live at East West Studios in West [[Hollywood, California]]. In early 2013, Corelia provided direct support to [[Misery Signals]] on their US tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/misery_signals_announce_tour_with_corelia |title=Misery Signals announce tour with Corelia |publisher=AltPress.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> and planned to release their debut LP in the fall of 2013, the follow-up to their EP, ''Nostalgia''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.revolvermag.com/news/exclusive-corelia-premiere-new-video-red-sky-harbor.html |title=Exclusive: Corelia Premiere New Music Video, \"Red Sky Harbor\" |publisher=RevolverMag.com |accessdate=2013-10-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020074840/http://www.revolvermag.com/news/exclusive-corelia-premiere-new-video-red-sky-harbor.html |archive-date=2013-10-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On January 21, 2015, Corelia created an Indiegogo.com campaign for their debut album, which received almost double its goal in a month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/corelia-2015-the-long-awaited-debut-album |title=CORELIA 2015 - The Long-Awaited Debut Album |publisher=indiegogo.com |accessdate=2015-01-21}}</ref> Along with releasing the campaign, they also announced that the album will be a 90 minute long, double disc album. The campaign promised a release date within 2015 but to date nothing has been released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/corelia-2015-the-long-awaited-debut-album |title=CORELIA 2015 - The Long-Awaited Debut Album |publisher=indiegogo.com |accessdate=2015-01-21}}</ref>\n\n==Tours==\n*Participated in a United States tour providing direct support to [[Misery Signals]] (January - February 2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/misery_signals_announce_tour_with_corelia |title=Misery Signals announce tour with Corelia |publisher=AltPress.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> \n*Participated in a United States tour with Seeker and I Omega (February 2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://got-djent.com/article/corelia-seeker-us-tour-announced |title=Corelia, Seeker: US tour announced |publisher=Got-Djent.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n;Current members\n*Ryan Devlin - vocals <small>(2010&ndash;2015)</small>\n*Chris Dower - guitar <small>(2010&ndash;2015)</small>\n*Clayton Pratt - drums, percussion <small>(2010&ndash;2015)</small>\n\n;Previous members\n*Ryan Borrell - guitar <small>(2010&ndash;2014)</small>\n*Adrian Alperstein - bass <small>(2010&ndash;2014)</small>\n\n==Discography==\n\n;EPs\n* ''Nostalgia'' (self-released, 2011)\n* ''Nostalgia (Instrumentals and Extras)'' (self-released, 2012)\n\n;Singles\n* ''Glass Faces'' (Instrumental)\n* ''Red Sky Harbor'' (Instrumental)\n* ''Aviation'' (Instrumental)\n* ''Glass Faces'' (Demo)\n* ''Aviation'' (Demo)\n* ''The Sound of Glaciers Moving''\n\n== Music videos ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Song\n! Director\n|-\n| 2012\n| \"The Sound of Glaciers Moving\"\n| Jeff Thomas\n|-\n| 2013\n| \"Red Sky Harbor\"\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://corelia.bandcamp.com BandCamp]\n*[https://myspace.com/corelliasd MySpace]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:CORELIA}}\n[[Category:American progressive metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:American instrumental musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2010]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Corelia\n| image            = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[San Diego, California]], [[United States]]\n| genre            =\n| years_active     = 2010 - 2016\n| label            = Unsigned\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = \n| current_members  = Ryan Devlin<br>Chris Dower<br>\n}}\n\n'''Corelia''' was a [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band from [[San Diego, California]]. The band was managed by Outerloop Management until October 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2017/06/19/its-time-for-you-to-give-up-and-stop-asking-about-corelia/ |title=It's Time For You to Give Up and Stop Asking About Corelia |publisher=MetalSucks.net |accessdate=2017-07-05}}</ref> and have released two EPs, ''Nostalgia'' (2011), and ''Nostalgia (Instrumentals and Extras)'' (2012).).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corelia.bandcamp.com/ |title=Corelia Releases |publisher=BandCamp.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> The band has caused controversy with their failure to produce a debut album as they had raised over $30,000 via crowdfunding platform Indiegogo, but have presented little to no evidence of an upcoming album. Due to the lack of updates, or any media presence at all, Corelia has been considered to be disbanded.<ref>http://www.metalsucks.net/2016/10/20/corelia-crowdfunding-campaign-leaves-fans-furious/</ref>\n\nOn April 11th, 2020, an anonymous individual claiming to be a former member of the band (presumed to be Clayton Pratt), created a separate facebook page titled \u201cCorelias\u201d <ref>https://m.facebook.com/Corelias-103850924626674/</ref>, and announced that he had a copy of the unreleased album and attempted to release it to the public on April 20th, 2020, without the formal authorization of the remaining band members. Though it was proven to be a hoax <ref> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LNGO3KoDB8s&feature=youtu.be&fbclid=IwAR19ePZWBey6MXYlr-wjENKTRXaI3NO3KJVrlfXXUJCs1WqfBgmaTD7PHAM </ref>, the band initially believed it to be credible and made their first public comment in nearly four years. <ref> https://www.facebook.com/coreliaofficial/?__tn__=kC-R&eid=ARDtNWk7yieCx3ca7waxZLX5tcN6OlHSeln_6vqrWApzKdA3EdTu1SQtMIqBh-CWTKOcHi3vF_Vh9H7P&hc_ref=ARSZJSS9BqARVBZVsdZZ_WmjuuRKpiyiNEFiwwh0XZcV_3ffZb5BcqGmymth2UnRW3k&fref=nf&__xts__[0]=68.ARBRJugbK65Sz-fPD2_H16vOwic5VxaHcZZIqmeVzuoovWVmX-B9HNlJsXw9RKLY5gLd4t9jVWrbIJybeN86vPKLM7Zh-ZCJG3clzXZ4DB8Exh9I0Y9SPUQpNOj8g-NzRLAhiJUic84U5YbN8y6UloHwkf-NIhN_zTcnlejxdGhQvToq7AG6mrh6TbNjJguQ23a7BYLAhOFiNJVf-fwOBmiw6LuuEBzyiyVZV48lIItSA0Lf5vMhoXsXw2zWEvNQ9hDi8tM7yZ62cTVNrsdHj2hxbQwYvrnq6iFGyV5PmZY4hDgAhJDBWn9_MQKlWGLnG1O5POi0dzomLAmXsr-e9Q </ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and ''Nostalgia'' releases (2010&ndash;2012)===\nCorelia formed in [[San Diego, California]] in 2010 by guitarist Chris Dower and drummer Clayton Pratt. Bassist Adrian Alperstein was added to the lineup a few months after the band\u2019s original formation, and in early 2010 the band completed their lineup with vocalist Ryan Devlin and guitarist Ryan Borrell. Throughout this process of finding band members, the band released several demos online.  In September 2011, the band put out their debut release titled ''Nostalgia''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Corelia/ |title=Corelia |publisher=Last.fm |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://got-djent.com/band/corelia |title=Corelia |publisher=Got-Djent.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> ''Nostalgia'' received a 4.5/Superb rating via Sputnik Music with an overall review summary by  Tim Perez, \"painstakingly refined over the years, the work of Corelia finally sees fruition in the form of a fantastic EP.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/45485/Corelia-Nostalgia |title=Corelia Nostalgia |publisher=SputnikMusic.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> The track entitled \u201cTreetops\u201d features guest vocals from original vocalist of Corelia and current vocalist of [[Periphery (band)|Periphery]], Spencer Sotelo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinsider.net/unsigned-streamed/unsigned-streamed-corelia |title=Unsigned & Streamed: Corelia |publisher=MetalInsider.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.revolvermag.com/news/exclusive-corelia-premiere-new-video-red-sky-harbor.html |title=Exclusive: Corelia Premiere New Music Video, \"Red Sky Harbor\" |publisher=RevolverMag.com |accessdate=2013-10-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020074840/http://www.revolvermag.com/news/exclusive-corelia-premiere-new-video-red-sky-harbor.html |archive-date=2013-10-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Vocalist Ryan Devlin filled in for [[The Human Abstract (band)|The Human Abstract]] on vocals on the \"Frak The Gods Tour\" with [[Periphery (band)|Periphery]] (US) and [[Suicide Silence]] (EU) in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinsider.net/unsigned-streamed/unsigned-streamed-corelia |title=Unsigned & Streamed: Corelia |publisher=MetalInsider.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2011/08/24/breaking-travis-richter-officially-out-of-the-human-abstract-corelias-ryan-devlin-named-as-touring-vocalist/ |title=BREAKING: TRAVIS RICHTER OFFICIALLY OUT OF THE HUMAN ABSTRACT, CORELIA\u2019S RYAN DEVLIN NAMED AS TOURING VOCALIST |publisher=MetalSucks.net |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> Corelia was endorsed by Ernie Ball Music Man, Warwick, Toontrack, and Venus Fallen.\n\n===\"New Album\" (2013&ndash;2016)===\nThe band began writing in early 2013. Corelia played a new song entitled \"Ages Ago\" in at Gallery 127 in [[El Paso, Texas]] on February 20, 2013. The track comes in at under three minutes, which makes it their shortest song yet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/av/corelia-premiere-new-song-live |title=CORELIA Premiere New Song Live |publisher=MetalInjection.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> Corelia teamed up with [[Revolver Magazine]] to debut their new music video, \u201cRed Sky Harbor,\u201d which was shot live at East West Studios in West [[Hollywood, California]]. In early 2013, Corelia provided direct support to [[Misery Signals]] on their US tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/misery_signals_announce_tour_with_corelia |title=Misery Signals announce tour with Corelia |publisher=AltPress.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> and planned to release their debut LP in the fall of 2013, the follow-up to their EP, ''Nostalgia''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.revolvermag.com/news/exclusive-corelia-premiere-new-video-red-sky-harbor.html |title=Exclusive: Corelia Premiere New Music Video, \"Red Sky Harbor\" |publisher=RevolverMag.com |accessdate=2013-10-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020074840/http://www.revolvermag.com/news/exclusive-corelia-premiere-new-video-red-sky-harbor.html |archive-date=2013-10-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On January 21, 2015, Corelia created an Indiegogo.com campaign for their debut album, which received almost double its goal in a month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/corelia-2015-the-long-awaited-debut-album |title=CORELIA 2015 - The Long-Awaited Debut Album |publisher=indiegogo.com |accessdate=2015-01-21}}</ref> Along with releasing the campaign, they also announced that the album will be a 90 minute long, double disc album. The campaign promised a release date within 2015 but to date nothing has been released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/corelia-2015-the-long-awaited-debut-album |title=CORELIA 2015 - The Long-Awaited Debut Album |publisher=indiegogo.com |accessdate=2015-01-21}}</ref>\n\n==Tours==\n*Participated in a United States tour providing direct support to [[Misery Signals]] (January - February 2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/misery_signals_announce_tour_with_corelia |title=Misery Signals announce tour with Corelia |publisher=AltPress.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> \n*Participated in a United States tour with Seeker and I Omega (February 2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://got-djent.com/article/corelia-seeker-us-tour-announced |title=Corelia, Seeker: US tour announced |publisher=Got-Djent.com |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n;Current members\n*Ryan Devlin - vocals <small>(2010&ndash;2015)</small>\n*Chris Dower - guitar <small>(2010&ndash;2015)</small>\n*Clayton Pratt - drums, percussion <small>(2010&ndash;2015)</small>\n\n;Previous members\n*Ryan Borrell - guitar <small>(2010&ndash;2014)</small>\n*Adrian Alperstein - bass <small>(2010&ndash;2014)</small>\n\n==Discography==\n\n;EPs\n* ''Nostalgia'' (self-released, 2011)\n* ''Nostalgia (Instrumentals and Extras)'' (self-released, 2012)\n\n;Singles\n* ''Glass Faces'' (Instrumental)\n* ''Red Sky Harbor'' (Instrumental)\n* ''Aviation'' (Instrumental)\n* ''Glass Faces'' (Demo)\n* ''Aviation'' (Demo)\n* ''The Sound of Glaciers Moving''\n\n== Music videos ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Song\n! Director\n|-\n| 2012\n| \"The Sound of Glaciers Moving\"\n| Jeff Thomas\n|-\n| 2013\n| \"Red Sky Harbor\"\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://corelia.bandcamp.com BandCamp]\n*[https://myspace.com/corelliasd MySpace]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:CORELIA}}\n[[Category:American progressive metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:American instrumental musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2010]]\n", "name_user": "2601:902:c200:8190:2d6c:e67:f087:a273", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corelia"}
{"title_page": "Pre-Pyrenees", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain range\n|name=Pre-Pyrenees\n|other_name=\n|photo=SERRAT DE FONTFREDA - MONTSEC D'ARES - IB-530.jpg \n|photo_caption=[[Montsec d'Ares]], part of the Pyrenees Foothills\n|country=[[Spain]]|country1=[[France]]|country2=|country3=\n|country4=|country5=|country6=|country7=\n|state_type=\n|region=\n|region1=\n|region2=\n|region3=\n|region4=\n|region5=\n|border=| border1=\n|geology= | geology1=| geology2=| geology3=| period= | orogeny=[[Alpine orogeny]]\n|area_km2= |highest=\n|elevation_m=\n|coordinates = \n| length_km= 425| length_orientation= E/W\n| width_km=  40 | width_orientation=N/S\n|range_coordinates = {{coord|42|20|N|1|0|E|type:mountain|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| map_image=Pyrenees topographic map-en.svg\n| map_caption= Topographic map of the Pyrenees\n}}\n[[File:Catmorfo.png|thumb|250px|Geomorphologic map of Catalonia: \n{{unbulleted list\n|{{legend2|#ff3f3f|[[Pyrenees]] }}\n|{{legend2|#ffa545|Pre-Pyrenees }}\n|{{legend2|#fff915|[[Catalan Central Depression]]}}\n|{{legend2|#d8c03d|Smaller mountain ranges of the Central Depression }}\n|{{legend2|#917654|[[Catalan Transversal Range]] }}\n|{{legend2|#487048|[[Catalan Pre-Coastal Range]] }}\n|{{legend2|#679772|[[Catalan Coastal Range]] }}\n|{{legend2|#a0d486|[[Catalan Coastal Depression]] and other coastal and pre-coastal plains}}\n}}]]\n\nThe '''Pre-Pyrenees''' are the [[foothills]] of the [[Pyrenees]].\n\n==Description==\nAs a mountainous system the Pre-Pyrenees are part of the Pyrenees. They run parallel to the main mountain range in a west to east direction. \n\nOn the French side the Pyrenees's slopes descend rather abruptly, thus on the northern side, the Pre-Pyrenees are confined to the [[Corbi\u00e8res Massif]], towards the eastern end of the mountain system.<ref> Christophe Neff : ''Les Corbi\u00e8res maritimes \u2013 forment-elles un \u00e9tage de v\u00e9g\u00e9tation m\u00e9diterran\u00e9enne thermophile masqu\u00e9 par la pression humaine ?'' In: Eric Fouache (Edit.): ''The Mediterranean World Environment and History. IAG Working Group on Geo-archeology, Symposium Proceedings. Environmental Dynamics and History in Mediterranean Areas, Paris, Universit\u00e9 de Paris \u2013 Sorbonne 24 \u2013 26 avril 2002''. Paris, 2003, 191 \u2013 202, (Elsevier France, {{ISBN|2-84299-452-3}}).</ref> The [[Massif de Plantaurel]] further west deserves mention as well, although not as clearly a foothill.\n\nOn the Iberian side, however, the picture is very different: a large and complex system of [[foothill]] ranges stretches from [[Navarre]], across northern [[Aragon]], reaching the [[Mediterranean]] coast on the [[Catalonia|Catalan]] end of the Pyrenees. At the eastern end on the southern side lies a distinct area known as the [[Sub-Pyrenees]].<ref>Jordi Sacasas i Llu\u00eds, ''Geograf\u00eda de Catalunya'', Publicacions L'Abadia de Montserrat. {{ISBN|978-84-8415-915-5}}</ref>\n\n==Main ranges==\nAlthough the highest peaks in the Pre-Pyrenees are not as high as those in the [[Pyrenees]] proper, some of the ranges are quite massive, with summits reaching up to {{convert|2600|m|abbr=on}}.<ref>[http://www10.gencat.net/probert/catala/prop_lleure/pdf/pirineusprepirineus.pdf Pirineus-Prepirineus] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723144756/http://www10.gencat.net/probert/catala/prop_lleure/pdf/pirineusprepirineus.pdf |date=2008-07-23 }}</ref> \n\n===Northern slope===\n*[[Corbi\u00e8res Massif]]\n*[[Massif de Plantaurel]]\n\n===Southern slope===\nThe main ranges are:\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;In Catalonia\n*[[Serra d'Auben\u00e7]]\n*[[Serra dels Bastets]]\n*[[Serra de Bellmunt]]\n*[[Cingles de Bev\u00ed]]\n*[[Serra de Boumort]]\n*[[Serra de Busa]]\n*[[Serra del Cad\u00ed]]\n**[[Montsec de Tost]]\n*[[Serra de Boumort]]\n*[[Serra de Camporan]]\n*[[Serra de les Canals]]\n*[[Serra de Capsacosta]]\n**[[Serra de Malforat]]\n***[[Serra de la Cau]]\n*[[Serra de Carreu]]\n*[[El Catllar\u00e0s]]\n*[[Serra de Comiols]]\n*[[Serra del Port del Comte]]\n**[[Serra de Querol]]\n**[[Serra del Verd]]\n*[[Serra de Conivella]]\n*[[Serrat de la Creueta (Das)|Serrat de la Creueta]]\n*[[Serra d'Ensija]]\n*[[La Faiada de Malp\u00e0s]]\n*[[Serra de Falgars]]\n*[[Serra de la Gessa]]\n*[[Serra de Sant Mamet]]\n*[[Serra de Moixer\u00f3]]\n*[[Serra de Milany]]\n*[[Mare de D\u00e9u del Mont]]\n*[[Serra de Monebui]]\n*[[Serra de Montcl\u00fas]]\n*[[Montsec]] range\n**[[Montsec de R\u00fabies]], the eastern massif, is separated by the river Segre in the east and the [[Noguera Pallaresa]] in the middle.\n***[[Serra del Cucuc]]\n**[[Montsec d'Ares]], the central massif. \n***[[Montrebei]]\n**[[Montsec d'Estall]], in [[Aragon]], located to the west, separated by the [[Noguera Ribagor\u00e7ana]] from the central massif.\n*[[Serra de Montgrony]]\n*[[Serra de Prada]]\n*[[Serra de Picamill]]\n*[[Serra de Picancel]]\n*[[Serra de Queralt (Bergued\u00e0)|Serra de Queralt]]\n*[[Serra de Sant Gerv\u00e0s]]\n**[[Serra de Setcomelles]]\n*[[Serra de Sant Joan (Coll de Narg\u00f3)|Serra de Sant Joan]]\n*[[Serra de Sant Marc]]\n*[[Serra de serra de Sobremunt]]\n*[[Serra del Volterol]]\n*[[Serra dels Tossals]]\n*[[Serra de Turp]]\n*[[Rasos de Peguera]]\n**[[Serrat de la Figuerassa]]\n;In Aragon\n*[[Sierra Caballera]]\n*[[Sierra del Castillo de Llaguarres]]\n*[[Sierra de la Carrodilla]]\n*[[Cotiella]]\n*[[Serra d'Esdolomada]]<ref>Luis Javier Cruchaga, ''Turb\u00f3n y Sierra de Sis,''Mapas excursionistas, no 12 PRAMES  2002 {{ISBN|84-8321-123-8}}</ref>\n*[[Sierra Ferrera]]\n*[[Sierra de Gir\u00f3]]\n*[[Serra del Jordal]]\n*[[Sierra de las Ares]]\n*[[Sierra de Guara]]\n*[[El Turb\u00f3n]]\n*[[Sierra de Sis]]\n*[[Sierra de Santo Domingo]]\n*[[Sierra de Loarre]]\n*[[Sierra de Javierre]]\n*[[Sierra Caballera]]\n;In Navarre\n*[[Sierra de Leire]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Features==\n{{Gallery\n|width=195\n|lines=4\n|File:El Turb\u00f3n.jpg|View of [[El Turb\u00f3n]] in [[Aragon]]\n|File:Gavet de la Conca. Sant Salvador de Tol\u00f3. Serra del Cucuc i Montsec de R\u00fabies 1.JPG|[[Serra del Cucuc]] and [[Montsec de R\u00fabies]] at [[Gavet de la Conca]]\n|File:Pic de Bugarach1.jpg|Summits of the [[Corbi\u00e8res Massif]], the only foothill of the Pyrenees on their northern side\n|File:Sierradecadi.jpg|View of [[Serra del Cad\u00ed]]\n|File:Serra Ferrera.jpg|View of [[Serra Ferrera]]\n|File:Serra de Sis (Prepirineus).jpg|View of the [[Mountains of Sis]]\n|File:El Cotiella vist des de la Serra del Jordal.jpg|[[Cotiella]]\n|File:Margues.jpg|View of [[Serra del Jordal]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Geology of the Pyrenees]]\n*[[Sub-Pyrenees]]\n*[[List of mountains in Catalonia]]\n*[[List of mountains in Aragon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category inline}}\n\n[[Category:Pre-Pyrenees| ]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Catalonia]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Aragon]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Navarre]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Occitanie]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain range\n|name=Pre-Pyrenees\n|other_name=\n|photo=SERRAT DE FONTFREDA - MONTSEC D'ARES - IB-530.jpg \n|photo_caption=[[Montsec d'Ares]], part of the Pyrenees Foothills\n|country=[[Spain]]|country1=[[France]]|country2=|country3=\n|country4=|country5=|country6=|country7=\n|state_type=\n|region=\n|region1=\n|region2=\n|region3=\n|region4=\n|region5=\n|border=| border1=\n|geology= | geology1=| geology2=| geology3=| period= | orogeny=[[Alpine orogeny]]\n|area_km2= |highest=\n|elevation_m=\n|coordinates = \n| length_km= 425| length_orientation= E/W\n| width_km=  40 | width_orientation=N/S\n|range_coordinates = {{coord|42|20|N|1|0|E|type:mountain|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| map_image=Pyrenees topographic map-en.svg\n| map_caption= Topographic map of the Pyrenees\n}}\n[[File:Catmorfo.png|thumb|250px|Geomorphologic map of Catalonia: \n{{unbulleted list\n|{{legend2|#ff3f3f|[[Pyrenees]] }}\n|{{legend2|#ffa545|Pre-Pyrenees }}\n|{{legend2|#fff915|[[Catalan Central Depression]]}}\n|{{legend2|#d8c03d|Smaller mountain ranges of the Central Depression }}\n|{{legend2|#917654|[[Catalan Transversal Range]] }}\n|{{legend2|#487048|[[Catalan Pre-Coastal Range]] }}\n|{{legend2|#679772|[[Catalan Coastal Range]] }}\n|{{legend2|#a0d486|[[Catalan Coastal Depression]] and other coastal and pre-coastal plains}}\n}}]]\n\nThe '''Pre-Pyrenees''' are the [[foothills]] of the [[Pyrenees]].\n\n==Description==\nAs a mountainous system the Pre-Pyrenees are part of the Pyrenees. They run parallel to the main mountain range in a west to east direction. \n\nOn the French side the Pyrenees's slopes descend rather abruptly, thus on the northern side, the Pre-Pyrenees are confined to the [[Corbi\u00e8res Massif]], towards the eastern end of the mountain system.<ref> Christophe Neff : ''Les Corbi\u00e8res maritimes \u2013 forment-elles un \u00e9tage de v\u00e9g\u00e9tation m\u00e9diterran\u00e9enne thermophile masqu\u00e9 par la pression humaine ?'' In: Eric Fouache (Edit.): ''The Mediterranean World Environment and History. IAG Working Group on Geo-archeology, Symposium Proceedings. Environmental Dynamics and History in Mediterranean Areas, Paris, Universit\u00e9 de Paris \u2013 Sorbonne 24 \u2013 26 avril 2002''. Paris, 2003, 191 \u2013 202, (Elsevier France, {{ISBN|2-84299-452-3}}).</ref> The [[Massif de Plantaurel]] further west deserves mention as well, although not as clearly a foothill.\n\nOn the Iberian side, however, the picture is very different: a large and complex system of [[foothill]] ranges stretches from [[Navarre]], across northern [[Aragon]], reaching the [[Mediterranean]] coast on the [[Catalonia|Catalan]] end of the Pyrenees. At the eastern end on the southern side lies a distinct area known as the [[Sub-Pyrenees]].<ref>Jordi Sacasas i Llu\u00eds, ''Geograf\u00eda de Catalunya'', Publicacions L'Abadia de Montserrat. {{ISBN|978-84-8415-915-5}}</ref>\n\n==Main ranges==\nAlthough the highest peaks in the Pre-Pyrenees are not as high as those in the [[Pyrenees]] proper, some of the ranges are quite massive, with summits reaching up to {{convert|2600|m|abbr=on}}.<ref>[http://www10.gencat.net/probert/catala/prop_lleure/pdf/pirineusprepirineus.pdf Pirineus-Prepirineus] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723144756/http://www10.gencat.net/probert/catala/prop_lleure/pdf/pirineusprepirineus.pdf |date=2008-07-23 }}</ref> \n\n===Northern slope===\n*[[Corbi\u00e8res Massif]]\n*[[Massif de Plantaurel]]\n\n===Southern slope===\nThe main ranges are:\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;In Catalonia\n*[[Serra d'Auben\u00e7]]\n*[[Serra dels Bastets]]\n*[[Serra de Bellmunt]]\n*[[Cingles de Bev\u00ed]]\n*[[Serra de Boumort]]\n*[[Serra de Busa]]\n*[[Serra del Cad\u00ed]]\n**[[Montsec de Tost]]\n*[[Serra de Boumort]]\n*[[Serra de Camporan]]\n*[[Serra de les Canals]]\n*[[Serra de Capsacosta]]\n**[[Serra de Malforat]]\n***[[Serra de la Cau]]\n*[[Serra de Carreu]]\n*[[El Catllar\u00e0s]]\n*[[Serra de Comiols]]\n*[[Serra del Port del Comte]]\n**[[Serra de Querol]]\n**[[Serra del Verd]]\n*[[Serra de Conivella]]\n*[[Serrat de la Creueta (Das)|Serrat de la Creueta]]\n*[[Serra d'Ensija]]\n*[[La Faiada de Malp\u00e0s]]\n*[[Serra de Falgars]]\n*[[Serra de la Gessa]]\n*[[Serra de Sant Mamet]]\n*[[Serra de Moixer\u00f3]]\n*[[Serra de Milany]]\n*[[Mare de D\u00e9u del Mont]]\n*[[Serra de Monebui]]\n*[[Serra de Montcl\u00fas]]\n*[[Montsec]] range\n**[[Montsec de R\u00fabies]], the eastern massif, is separated by the river Segre in the east and the [[Noguera Pallaresa]] in the middle.\n***[[Serra del Cucuc]]\n**[[Montsec d'Ares]], the central massif. \n***[[Montrebei]]\n**[[Montsec d'Estall]], in [[Aragon]], located to the west, separated by the [[Noguera Ribagor\u00e7ana]] from the central massif.\n*[[Serra de Montgrony]]\n*[[Serra de Prada]]\n*[[Serra de Picamill]]\n*[[Serra de Picancel]]\n*[[Serra de Queralt (Bergued\u00e0)|Serra de Queralt]]\n*[[Serra de Sant Gerv\u00e0s]]\n**[[Serra de Setcomelles]]\n*[[Serra de Sant Joan (Coll de Narg\u00f3)|Serra de Sant Joan]]\n*[[Serra de Sant Marc]]\n*[[Serra de serra de Sobremunt]]\n*[[Serra del Volterol]]\n*[[Serra dels Tossals]]\n*[[Serra de Turp]]\n*[[Rasos de Peguera]]\n**[[Serrat de la Figuerassa]]\n;In Aragon\n*[[Sierra Caballera]]\n*[[Sierra del Castillo de Llaguarres]]\n*[[Sierra de la Carrodilla]]\n*[[Cotiella]]\n*[[Serra d'Esdolomada]]<ref>Luis Javier Cruchaga, ''Turb\u00f3n y Sierra de Sis,''Mapas excursionistas, no 12 PRAMES  2002 {{ISBN|84-8321-123-8}}</ref>\n*[[Sierra Ferrera]]\n*[[Sierra de Gir\u00f3]]\n*[[Serra del Jordal]]\n*[[Sierra de las Ares]]\n*[[Sierra de Guara]]\n*[[El Turb\u00f3n]]\n*[[Sierra de Sis]]\n*[[Sierra de Santo Domingo]]\n*[[Sierra de Loarre]]\n*[[Sierra de Javierre]]\n*[[Sierra Caballera]]\n;In Navarre\n*[[Sierra de Leire]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Features==\n{{Gallery\n|width=195\n|lines=4\n|File:El Turb\u00f3n.jpg|View of [[El Turb\u00f3n]] in [[Aragon]]\n|File:Gavet de la Conca. Sant Salvador de Tol\u00f3. Serra del Cucuc i Montsec de R\u00fabies 1.JPG|[[Serra del Cucuc]] and [[Montsec de R\u00fabies]] at [[Gavet de la Conca]]\n|File:Pic de Bugarach1.jpg|Summits of the [[Corberes range]], the only foothill of the Pyrenees on their northern side\n|File:Sierradecadi.jpg|View of [[Serra del Cad\u00ed]]\n|File:Serra Ferrera.jpg|View of [[Serra Ferrera]]\n|File:Serra de Sis (Prepirineus).jpg|View of the [[Mountains of Sis]]\n|File:El Cotiella vist des de la Serra del Jordal.jpg|[[Cotiella]]\n|File:Margues.jpg|View of [[Serra del Jordal]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Geology of the Pyrenees]]\n*[[Sub-Pyrenees]]\n*[[List of mountains in Catalonia]]\n*[[List of mountains in Aragon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category inline}}\n\n[[Category:Pre-Pyrenees| ]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Catalonia]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Aragon]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Navarre]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Occitanie]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "use same link through