2 | first = Mike | last = McGee | dab = basketball | num = 40 | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 5 | lbs = 190 | school = Michigan | DOB = 1959\u201307\u201329}}\n{{player2 | first = Steve | last = Mix | num = 50 | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 7 | lbs = 215 | school = Toledo | DOB = 1947\u201312\u201330}}\n{{player2 | first = Norm | last = Nixon | num = 10 | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 2 | lbs = 170 | school = Duquesne | DOB = 1955\u201310\u201311}}\n{{player2 | first = Kurt | last = Rambis | num = 31 | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 8 | lbs = 213 | school = Santa Clara | DOB = 1958\u201302\u201325}}\n{{player2 | first = Jamaal | last = Wilkes | num = 52 | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 6 | lbs = 190 | school = UCLA | DOB = 1953\u201305\u201302}}\n{{player2 | first = James | last = Worthy | num = 42 | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 9 | lbs = 225 | school = North Carolina | DOB = 1961\u201302\u201327}}\n<!-- end list of players -->\n{{NBA roster footer\n| head_coach = \n* {{player||USA|[[Pat Riley]]}} ({{college|Kentucky}})\n| asst_coach =\n* {{player||USA|[[Bill Bertka]]}} ({{college|Kent State}})\n* {{player||USA|[[Dave Wohl]]}} ({{college|Pennsylvania}})\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1983 NBA Playoffs]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/65cZRcpol?url=http://www.nba.com/history/finals/19821983.html NBA History]\n\n{{NBA Finals}}\n{{Philadelphia 76ers 1982\u201383 NBA champions}}\n{{Philadelphia 76ers}}\n{{Los Angeles Lakers}}\n{{1982\u201383 NBA season by team}}\n{{NBA on CBS}}\n{{NBA on Mutual}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1983 Nba Finals}}\n[[Category:National Basketball Association Finals]]\n[[Category:1982\u201383 NBA season|Finals]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia 76ers games|NBA]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Lakers games|NBA]]\n[[Category:1983 in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:1983 in sports in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1980s in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:May 1983 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Inglewood, California]]\n[[Category:1983 in sports in California|NBA]]\n", "text_old": "{{tone|date=September 2015}}\n{{NBA Finals summary\n| image =\n| caption =\n| league = NBA\n| year = 1983\n| runnerup = [[1982\u201383 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| runnerup_coach = [[Pat Riley]]\n| runnerup_games = 0\n| champion = [[1982\u201383 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]]\n| champion_coach = [[Billy Cunningham]]\n| champion_games = 4\n| date = May 22\u201331\n| MVP = [[Moses Malone]]<br />(Philadelphia 76ers)\n| television = [[NBA on CBS|CBS]] (U.S.)\n| announcers = [[Dick Stockton]] and [[Bill Russell]]\n| HOFers = '''76ers:'''<br />[[Maurice Cheeks]] (2018)<br />[[Julius Erving]] (1993)<br />[[Bobby Jones (basketball, born 1951)|Bobby Jones]] (2019)<br />[[Moses Malone]] (2001)<br />'''Lakers:'''<br />[[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] (1995)<br />[[Magic Johnson]] (2002)<br />[[Bob McAdoo]] (2000)<br />[[Jamaal Wilkes]] (2012)<br />[[James Worthy]] (2003; did not play)<br />'''Coaches:'''<br />Billy Cunningham (1986, player)<br />Pat Riley (2008)<br />'''Broadcasters:'''<br />[[Chick Hearn]] (2003, contributor)<br />'''Officials:'''<br />[[Darell Garretson]] (2016)<br />[[Earl Strom]] (1995)\n| radio_network = [[Mutual Broadcasting Network|Mutual]] (U.S.)<br>WFIL (PHI)<br>KLAC (LAL)\n| radio_announcers = [[Tony Roberts (sportscaster)|Tony Roberts]] and [[Tom Heinsohn]] (Mutual)<br>[[Neil Funk]] (76ers)<br>[[Chick Hearn]] and [[Keith Erickson]] (Lakers)\n| referees_1 = [[Jack Madden]] and [[Ed T. Rush]]\n| referees_2 = [[Darell Garretson]] and [[John Vanak]]\n| referees_3 = [[Jess Kersey]] and [[Jake O'Donnell]]\n| referees_4 = [[Hugh Evans (basketball referee)|Hugh Evans]] and [[Earl Strom]]\n| ECF result = [[1982\u201383 Philadelphia 76ers season|76ers]] defeat [[1982\u201383 Milwaukee Bucks season|Bucks]], 4\u20131\n| WCF result = [[1982\u201383 Los Angeles Lakers season|Lakers]] defeat [[1982\u201383 San Antonio Spurs season|Spurs]], 4\u20132\n}}\n\nThe '''1983 NBA World Championship Series''', also known as '''Showdown '83''', was the championship round of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA)'s [[1982\u201383 NBA season|1982\u201383 season]], and the culmination of the [[1983 NBA Playoffs|season's playoffs]]. It was the last NBA Championship Series completed before June 1.<!--- last to finish before May 1 was the [[1971 NBA Finals]] ---> The [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] champion [[1982\u201383 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]] defeated the [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] champion [[1982\u201383 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]] 4 games to 0. 76ers center [[Moses Malone]] was named the [[Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award|NBA Finals Most Valuable Player]] (MVP).\n\n==Background==\n\n===Philadelphia 76ers===\n{{main article|1982\u201383 Philadelphia 76ers season}}\nThe 76ers lost their first two Finals meetings with the Lakers in {{nbafy|1980}} and {{nbafy|1982}}. While [[Julius Erving]] played superbly in both series, their frontcourt of [[Darryl Dawkins]], [[Caldwell Jones]] and [[Bobby Jones (basketball, born 1951)|Bobby Jones]] couldn't neutralize [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]]. So in the off-season, the 76ers acquired [[Moses Malone]] from the [[1982\u201383 Houston Rockets season|Houston Rockets]] in an effort to counter Abdul-Jabbar, in addition to providing some offense and rebounding to the team. They parted ways with Caldwell Jones, Dawkins, and [[Lionel Hollins]] before the season, while giving greater responsibility to high-scoring guard [[Andrew Toney]] and backup playmaker [[Clint Richardson]], and adding forwards [[Clemon Johnson]] and rookie [[Marc Iavaroni]].\n\nMalone's acquisition paid dividends, as the 76ers won 65 games in the [[1982\u201383 NBA season]]. Prior to the [[1983 NBA Playoffs|playoffs]], Malone predicted the team would win in four games in each of the three rounds, ending it with the statement ''Fo, Fo, Fo''. The 76ers would steamroll through the playoffs, sweeping the [[1982\u201383 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]] 4\u20130 in the conference semifinals, before overcoming the [[1982\u201383 Milwaukee Bucks season|Milwaukee Bucks]] in five games\n\n===Los Angeles Lakers===\n{{main article|1982\u201383 Los Angeles Lakers season}}\nThe Lakers earned the top pick of the [[1982 NBA draft]], becoming the only defending champion to earn the top overall pick in the same season. This was because [[1979\u201380 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cleveland Cavaliers]] owner [[Ted Stepien]] traded their first round pick and [[Butch Lee]] to the Lakers for [[Don Ford]] and draft pick [[Chad Kinch]] [[1979\u201380 NBA season|three years earlier]]. Because the Cavaliers earned the worst record at 15\u201367, they would have earned the top overall pick via a coin toss with the 17\u201365 [[1981\u201382 San Diego Clippers season|San Diego Clippers]]. Instead, the Lakers would earn the top pick and ultimately selected future [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Hall of Famer]] [[James Worthy]] first overall.\n\nThe Lakers won 58 games the next season. Worthy was a strong contender for [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]] when he broke his leg late in the season, therefore missing the rest of the season and the playoffs. Despite Worthy's absence, Magic Johnson and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar were still in their prime, and led the Lakers back to the Finals by beating the [[1982\u201383 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]] 4\u20131 and the [[1982\u201383 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]] 4\u20132 in the second and third playoff rounds, respectively.\n\n===Road to the Finals===\n{{Main|1983 NBA Playoffs}}\n{| style=\"width:100%; font-size:90%\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=top\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:45%;\"|[[Los Angeles Lakers]] ([[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] champion) !! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:45%;\"|[[Philadelphia 76ers]] ([[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] champion)\n|-\n|align=right|\n{{1982\u201383 NBA West standings|team=LAL}}1st seed in the West, 2nd best league record\n!colspan=2|[[1982\u201383 NBA season|Regular season]]\n|\n{{1982\u201383 NBA East standings|team=PHI}}1st seed in the East, best league record\n|-\n|align=right|Earned first-round bye\n!colspan=2|First Round\n|Earned first-round bye\n|-\n|align=right|Defeated the (5) [[1982\u201383 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]], 4\u20131\n!colspan=2|Conference Semifinals\n|Defeated the (5) [[1982\u201383 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]], 4\u20130\n|-\n|align=right|Defeated the (2) [[1982\u201383 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]], 4\u20132\n!colspan=2|Conference Finals\n|Defeated the (2) [[1982\u201383 Milwaukee Bucks season|Milwaukee Bucks]], 4\u20131\n|}\n\n===Regular season series===\nThe [[Philadelphia 76ers]] won both games in the regular season series:\n{{basketballbox\n | bg=#fff\n | date = December 5, 1982\n | team1 = '''[[Philadelphia 76ers]] |score1=114'''\n | team2 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]] |score2=104\n | place = [[The Forum (Inglewood)|The Forum]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n }}\n{{basketballbox\n | date = January 5, 1983\n | team1 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]] |score1=120\n | team2 = '''[[Philadelphia 76ers]] |score2=122''' (OT)\n | place = [[Spectrum (arena)|The Spectrum]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n}}\n\n==Series summary==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Game !! Date !! Home Team !! Result!! Road Team\n|-\n|Game 1 || Sunday, May 22 || '''Philadelphia 76ers''' || 113\u2013107 (1\u20130) || Los Angeles Lakers\n|-\n|Game 2 || Thursday, May 26 || '''Philadelphia 76ers''' || 103\u201393 (2\u20130) || Los Angeles Lakers\n|-\n|Game 3 || Sunday, May 29 || Los Angeles Lakers || 94\u2013111 (0\u20133) || '''Philadelphia 76ers'''\n|-\n|Game 4 || Tuesday, May 31 || Los Angeles Lakers || 108\u2013115 (0\u20134) || '''Philadelphia 76ers'''\n|}\n\nThe final piece of the [[Philadelphia 76ers]]' championship puzzle was completed before the 1982\u201383 season when they acquired center [[Moses Malone]] from the [[Houston Rockets]]. They went on to capture their historic second NBA championship as they won 65 games, and stormed through the [[1983 NBA Playoffs|playoffs]], first sweeping the [[New York Knicks]], and then beating the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] in five games. They finally finished it off with a four-game sweep of the [[Los Angeles Lakers]], who had defeated them the season before.\n\nSaid head coach [[Billy Cunningham]], ''\"The difference from last year was Moses.\"'' Malone was named MVP of the 1983 Finals, as well as league MVP for the third time in his career. The 76ers completed one of the most dominating playoff runs in league history with a 12\u20131 mark after league and NBA Finals MVP Moses promised ''\"Fo', fo', fo\"'' (as in ''\"four, four, four\"''\u2014four wins to win round 1, four wins to win round 2, etc.), but it actually wound up as ''\"Fo', fi', fo.\"'' (four, five, four). The 76ers were also led by [[Julius Erving]], [[Maurice Cheeks]], [[Andrew Toney]], and [[Bobby Jones (basketball, born 1951)|Bobby Jones]].\n\nWith 59 seconds to go in Game 4, it was Erving who made a three-point play to hold the lead for good, crushing the Lakers in a four-game sweep and ending the last NBA Finals to end before June.\n\n===Game 1===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=May 22 |time=3:35 p.m. EDT |place=[[Spectrum (arena)|The Spectrum]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] |TV=[[NBA on CBS|CBS]]\n|team1=[[Los Angeles Lakers]] |score1=107\n|team2='''[[Philadelphia 76ers]] |score2=113'''\n|report=\n|Q1=20\u201330 |Q2=37\u201324 |Q3=26\u201331 |Q4=24\u201328\n|points1=[[Norm Nixon]] 26 |points2=[[Moses Malone]] 27\n|rebounds1=[[Mark Landsberger]] 10 |rebounds2=[[Moses Malone]] 18\n|assist1=[[Magic Johnson]] 11 |assist2=[[Julius Erving]] 9\n|attendance=18,482\n|referee=<br />\n* No. 14 Jack Madden\n* No. 4 Ed T. Rush\n|series=Philadelphia leads the series, 1\u20130\n}}\n\n===Game 2===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=May 26 |time=9:05 p.m. EDT |place=[[Spectrum (arena)|The Spectrum]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] |TV=[[NBA on CBS|CBS]]\n|team1=[[Los Angeles Lakers]] |score1=93\n|team2='''[[Philadelphia 76ers]] |score2=103'''\n|report=\n|Q1=29\u201326 |Q2=26\u201325 |Q3=20\u201328 |Q4=18\u201324\n|points1=[[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] 23 |points2=[[Moses Malone]] 24\n|rebounds1=[[Magic Johnson]] 8 |rebounds2=[[Moses Malone]] 12\n|assist1=[[Magic Johnson]] 13 |assist2=[[Maurice Cheeks]] 8\n|attendance=18,482\n|referee=<br />\n* No. 10 Darell Garretson\n* No. 9 John Vanak\n* No. 12 Earl Strom (alternate)\n|series=Philadelphia leads the series, 2\u20130\n}}\n\n===Game 3===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=May 29 |time=12:35 p.m. PDT |place=[[The Forum (Inglewood)|The Forum]], [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]], [[California]] |TV=[[NBA on CBS|CBS]]\n|team1='''[[Philadelphia 76ers]] |score1=111'''\n|team2=[[Los Angeles Lakers]] |score2=94\n|report=\n|Q1=21\u201332 |Q2=28\u201320 |Q3=23\u201320 |Q4=39\u201322\n|points1=[[Moses Malone]] 28 |points2=[[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] 23\n|rebounds1=[[Moses Malone]] 19 |rebounds2=[[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] 15\n|assist1=[[Moses Malone]] 6 |assist2=[[Magic Johnson]] 13\n|attendance=17,505\n|referee=<br />\n* No. 20 Jess Kersey\n* No. 11 Jake O'Donnell\n|series=Philadelphia leads the series, 3\u20130\n}}\n\n===Game 4===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=May 31 |time=6:05 p.m. PDT |place=[[The Forum (Inglewood)|The Forum]], [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]], [[California]] |TV=[[NBA on CBS|CBS]]\n|team1='''[[Philadelphia 76ers]] |score1=115'''\n|team2=[[Los Angeles Lakers]] |score2=108\n|report=\n|Q1=24\u201326 |Q2=27\u201339 |Q3=31\u201328 |Q4=33\u201315\n|points1=[[Moses Malone]] 24 |points2=[[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] 28\n|rebounds1=[[Moses Malone]] 23 |rebounds2=[[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar|Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Magic Johnson|Johnson]], [[Mark Landsberger|Landsberger]], [[Mike McGee (basketball)|McGee]] 7 each\n|assist1=[[Andrew Toney]] 9 |assist2=[[Magic Johnson]] 15\n|attendance=17,505\n|referee=<br />\n* No. 25 Hugh Evans\n* No. 12 Earl Strom\n* No. 20 Jess Kersey (alternate)\n|series=Philadelphia wins the series, 4\u20130\n}}\n\n==Player statistics==\n{{NBA roster statistics legend}}\n\n;Philadelphia 76ers\n{{NBA roster statistics start|team=Philadelphia 76ers}}\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Andrew|Toney}} || 4 || 4 || 36.8 || .423 || .000 || .848 || 2.3 || 5.8 || 1.3 || 0.3 || 22.0 \n|-! style=\"background:#FDE910;\"\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Moses|Malone}} || 4 || 4 || '''39.3''' || .507 || .000 || .660 || '''18.0''' || 2.0 || 1.5 || 1.5 || '''25.8''' \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Maurice|Cheeks}} || 4 || 4 || 35.8 || .553 || .000 || .600 || 2.3 || '''6.3''' || '''2.8''' || 0.0 || 15.3 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Bobby|Jones|Bobby Jones (basketball, born 1951)}} || 4 || 0 || 26.0 || .568 || .000 || .667 || 4.8 || 2.8 || 2.0 || 2.3 || 12.0 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Marc|Iavaroni}} || 4 || 4 || 24.8 || .588 || .000 || .375 || 5.5 || 2.0 || 0.3 || 0.8 || 5.8 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Julius|Erving}} || 4 || 4 || 38.3 || .469 || .000 || .800 || 8.5 || 5.0 || 1.3 || '''2.8''' || 19.0 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Clint|Richardson}} || 4 || 0 || 23.0 || .393 || .000 || .750 || 3.3 || 1.8 || 1.3 || 0.3 || 6.3 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Clemon|Johnson}} || 3 || 0 || 12.7 || .385 || .000 || .000 || 3.0 || 0.3 || 0.3 || 0.3 || 3.3 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Earl|Cureton}} || 3 || 0 || 6.3 || .333 || .000 || .000 || 1.0 || 0.3 || 0.7 || 0.0 || 0.7 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Mark|McNamara}} || 1 || 0 || 1.0 || '''1.000''' || .000 || .000 || 0.0 || 0.0 || 0.0 || 0.0 || 4.0 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Reggie|Johnson|Reggie Johnson (basketball, born 1957)}} || 1 || 0 || 1.0 || .000 || .000 || 